SIMPLE: gospeler
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Gospeler
<hw>Gos"pel*er</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[AS.
<ets>godspellere</ets>.]</ety> <altsp>[Written also
<asp>gospeller</asp>.]</altsp> <sn>1.</sn> <def>One of the four
evangelists.</def> <rj><au>Rom. of R.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Mark the <qex>gospeler</qex> was the ghostly son of Peter in
baptism.</q> <rj><qau>Wyclif.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A follower of Wycliffe, the first English religious
reformer; hence, a Puritan.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>
<rj><au>Latimer.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The persecution was carried on against the <qex>gospelers</qex>
with much fierceness by those of the Roman persuasion.</q>
<rj><qau>Strype.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A priest or deacon who reads the gospel at the altar
during the communion service.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The Archbishop of York was the celebrant, the epistoler being the
dean, and the <qex>gospeler</qex> the Bishop of Sydney.</q>
<rj><qau>Pall Mall Gazette.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Gospelize</ent>⟦br⟧
